  <h1>What to Do After a Defective Product Injury</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Auden Cordell (AC), Editor-in-Chief. Contributor: Holland Devlin (HD), Recall &amp; Consumer Safety Reference. Updated May 2026.</em></p>

  <p>The first 30 days after a defective-product injury determine how strong your case will be at every stage that follows. Most of the work is straightforward and free; it is also work that gets harder the longer you wait. This guide is the practical checklist we wish every reader had handed to them on the day of the injury.</p>

  <h2>Step 1 (immediate): Get medical care and follow through</h2>

  <p>Treat the injury as a medical event first and a legal event second. Go to the emergency room or urgent care if the injury is significant. Follow every recommendation: take the prescribed medication, attend the follow-up appointment, do the physical therapy. Two reasons. First, the medical outcome is the most important thing in your life right now. Second, gaps in treatment ("the plaintiff didn't even bother to follow up") are one of the most effective defense arguments against pain-and-suffering damages.</p>

  <p>Tell every treating provider exactly how the injury happened. "I was using a [product] and [specific failure]" should appear in the contemporaneous medical record. Vague history ("hand injury, accident") makes the case harder to prove later because the defendant will argue the injury came from something else.</p>

  <h2>Step 2 (within 24 hours): Preserve the product</h2>

  <p>This is the single most important step and the one most often missed. The defective product itself is the most important piece of evidence in your case. <strong>Do not</strong>:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Throw it away.</li>
    <li>Send it back to the manufacturer (this is what they will try to get you to do).</li>
    <li>Repair it or have it repaired.</li>
    <li>Allow anyone other than your attorney's investigator to handle it.</li>
    <li>Discard the packaging, instructions, receipt, or warranty card.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>Place the product in a sealed bag or box in its post-failure condition. Photograph it from every angle before bagging. Note the model number, serial number, lot number, and date code if you can read them on the product or the packaging. Store it somewhere dry and out of the way. The manufacturer's representative or insurer may ask for the product "for inspection"; politely refuse and tell them your attorney will arrange a joint inspection.</p>

  <p>Failure to preserve the product is the most common reason otherwise-good product liability cases fail. Without the product, the defendant can argue almost anything about the failure mode, and the plaintiff's expert has nothing to inspect.</p>

  <h2>Step 3 (within 48 hours): Photograph everything</h2>

  <p>Photograph the product (from every angle, with a scale reference if you have one). Photograph the scene where the injury occurred, especially if the failure produced secondary damage (fire damage to a room, water damage from a leak, vehicle damage from an airbag failure). Photograph your injuries before any treatment alters their appearance. Keep photographing injuries through the recovery process &mdash; weekly is not too often for serious injuries. Visible documentation of pain and disfigurement is one of the most powerful damages exhibits.</p>

  <p>Use a smartphone camera; modern phone cameras produce more than adequate evidentiary photographs. Make sure date and time stamps are enabled. Back up the photos to cloud storage so they cannot be lost if your phone is broken or stolen.</p>

  <h2>Step 4 (within 1 week): Document the chain of custody</h2>

  <p>Where did you buy the product? When? What store, what online retailer? Find the receipt, the email confirmation, the credit card statement entry. If the product was a gift, who gave it to you, when, and where did they buy it? If it was bought used, from whom? This chain matters because it identifies the defendants &mdash; manufacturer, distributor, retailer &mdash; and because it establishes the date of original sale (relevant to statute of repose questions).</p>

  <p>Save the original packaging and any inserts or instruction sheets. Save the warranty card. Save any registration paperwork. Take photographs of everything as a backup in case the originals are lost.</p>

  <h2>Step 5 (within 1 week): Identify witnesses</h2>

  <p>Did anyone see the injury occur? Did anyone see the product fail? Did anyone witness symptoms develop in the case of a pharmaceutical or food-contamination injury? Get their names, phone numbers, and email addresses while their memory is fresh. Ask them to write down what they saw in their own words, while it is fresh. Witnesses tend to scatter over time &mdash; people move, change jobs, lose touch. Locking down witness contact information in the first week is critical.</p>

  <h2>Step 6 (within 2 weeks): Research recalls</h2>

  <p>Check whether the product has been recalled. The three primary agency databases:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Consumer Product Safety Commission (CPSC) at <a href="https://www.cpsc.gov/Recalls" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">cpsc.gov/Recalls</a> &mdash; covers consumer products generally.</li>
    <li>National Highway Traffic Safety Administration (NHTSA) at <a href="https://www.nhtsa.gov/recalls" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">nhtsa.gov/recalls</a> &mdash; covers motor vehicles and motor vehicle equipment.</li>
    <li>Food and Drug Administration (FDA) at <a href="https://www.fda.gov/safety/recalls-market-withdrawals-safety-alerts" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">fda.gov/safety/recalls-market-withdrawals-safety-alerts</a> &mdash; covers drugs, medical devices, food, cosmetics.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>If you find a recall, save the recall notice in PDF form, note the recall date, and check whether the recall pre-dated your injury. A pre-injury recall is one of the strongest pieces of strict-liability evidence available.</p>

  <h2>Step 7 (within 2 weeks): Search for similar incidents</h2>

  <p>Other consumers injured by the same product will often have complained to the CPSC, FDA, NHTSA, or the Better Business Bureau, or posted about the failure on social media or in product reviews. Searching for "[product name] [failure mode]" on Google, Reddit, and the agency databases often turns up a pattern of similar failures. This pattern is powerful evidence in a design-defect case. Document what you find (screenshots, links) and save it for your attorney.</p>

  <h2>Step 8 (within 30 days): Find an attorney</h2>

  <p>Product liability is a specialist practice. Do not retain a general-practice personal-injury lawyer for a product case unless they have specific product-liability experience. The screening questions to ask:</p>

  <ul>
    <li>How many product liability cases have you tried to verdict in the last five years?</li>
    <li>Have you handled this specific product category (auto, pharma, medical device, consumer product) before?</li>
    <li>Do you have access to expert engineers/scientists in this product domain?</li>
    <li>Do you handle cases on contingency, and what is your standard contingency rate?</li>
    <li>How are case expenses handled, and who bears the loss if the case is unsuccessful?</li>
    <li>If this case develops into an MDL, are you in a position to participate?</li>
  </ul>

  <p>The initial consultation is almost always free. Bring everything you have collected: the product (or photographs of it), receipts, medical records, photographs of injuries, recall printouts, and notes on similar incidents. Most plaintiff-side product liability firms can assess a case within an hour of conversation and will tell you frankly whether it is one they would take.</p>

  <h2>Step 9 (ongoing): Note the statute of limitations</h2>

  <p>Personal-injury statute of limitations in product cases is typically 2&ndash;4 years from injury or reasonable discovery of the defect, depending on the state. The deadline is jurisdictional &mdash; missing it bars the claim regardless of merit. Once you retain counsel, the deadline is their responsibility, but it is still wise to write it on your own calendar.</p>

  <p>Statute of repose, where it applies, runs from the date of original sale of the product. A statute of repose bars even timely-filed claims if the product is too old. Confirm with counsel whether your state has one and whether your product is within the period.</p>

  <h2>Step 10 (ongoing): Do not talk to the manufacturer's insurer</h2>

  <p>The manufacturer's insurance representative will almost certainly contact you to "discuss the matter." They are not on your side. They will try to elicit recorded statements that can later be used against you, offer quick low-value settlements before the full extent of injury is known, or persuade you to send the product in for "inspection" (which means you lose it). Politely tell them to contact your attorney and end the conversation. If you have not yet retained counsel, tell them you will be in touch through your attorney once retained.</p>

  <p>For an overview of how the case will be valued once a lawyer takes it on, see <a href="/guides/how-product-liability-settlements-are-calculated">how product liability settlements are calculated</a>. For the legal theories that will apply, see <a href="/guides/types-of-product-defects-and-claim-theories">types of product defects and claim theories</a>. For common misconceptions to watch for, see <a href="/guides/common-product-liability-claim-misconceptions">common product liability claim misconceptions</a>.</p>
